            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Katherine Sharma\u2019s passion for cities was born from their absence. Raised in a sprawling, car-dependent Chicago suburb, her childhood was a landscape of cul-de-sacs and strip malls. The daughter of a pragmatic accountant and a high school teacher, she spent her youth sketching intricate city maps in her notebooks, imagining vibrant public squares and streets teeming with life, a stark contrast to the quiet homogeneity around her. This fascination led her to an undergraduate degree at the University of Illinois, but it was UC Berkeley\u2019s renowned Master of Urban Planning program that finally brought her west.\n\nArriving in the Bay Area was a revelation. Katherine was captivated by San Francisco's complex, chaotic, and beautiful urban fabric. After graduating, she took a junior position at a downtown design firm, eagerly diving into the city's notorious world of zoning codes, community feedback sessions, and seismic retrofitting. It was during this time she met her husband, Rohan Sharma, a software engineer whose logical, data-driven worldview provided a fascinating counterpoint to her own design-oriented perspective. They married and bought a condo in Hayes Valley, a neighborhood whose own revitalization story she deeply admired.\n\nNow, at 45, Katherine is a Principal Urban Designer, a respected voice who guides major public and private development projects. Her life is a testament to her professional principles. Her 1.1-mile walk to her SoMa office is the most cherished part of her day, a moving survey of her life\u2019s work. She passes the pocket park whose community approval she championed and the mixed-use building whose pedestrian-friendly ground floor she meticulously designed. Her routine is deeply local: morning coffee at a corner caf\u00e9, weekend strolls to the farmers' market, and serving on her local neighborhood association board.\n\nKatherine\u2019s professional success has brought comfort, but her ambition has shifted from climbing the career ladder to leaving a lasting, positive mark on her adopted home. She dreams of spearheading a legacy project\u2014one that tackles the city's affordability crisis or creates a truly resilient and equitable public space for all residents. More than just designing a city, Katherine Sharma aspires to help heal it."
        },
        {
            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1.\nShe was 22, fresh off the plane for her Berkeley orientation. Stepping out of the downtown Berkeley BART station, the sheer density of it all hit her like a physical force. The air tasted of diesel, salt, and eucalyptus; a street musician\u2019s sax riff blended with a current of languages she didn\u2019t recognize. This was it. This was the vibrant, chaotic, human-scaled world she had only ever been able to draw. In that moment, the loneliness of the suburbs finally evaporated, replaced by the thrilling anonymity and connection of a real city.\n\n2.\nAt 29, she sat through the fourth and final community meeting for a tiny pocket park in the Mission. A woman who\u2019d fiercely opposed the plan, fearing it would attract crime, approached her afterward. Her voice thick with emotion, she pointed to a small detail in the blueprint\u2014a bench placed to catch the morning sun. \u201cMy husband and I used to sit just like that,\u201d she whispered. Katherine realized then that urban planning wasn\u2019t about imposing a vision, but about finding and honoring the memories already embedded in a place.\n\n3.\nIt was at a dreadfully dry lecture on seismic retrofitting that she first noticed Rohan. He wasn't a designer; he'd asked a piercingly logical question about data modeling for liquefaction zones that made her see the problem in a new light. He found her afterward, and their debate over structural integrity turned into a coffee, then another. She fell for the elegant certainty of his code, a perfect, beautiful contrast to the messy, human complexity of her own work. He didn't just understand her passion; his logic helped ground it.\n\n4.\nThe first morning in their Hayes Valley condo, she woke not to an alarm, but to the city\u2019s rhythm: the metallic clang of a security gate rolling up, the distant chatter from the line at Blue Bottle, the hum from the arts patrons on their way to the symphony. Standing at the window with Rohan, a mug of coffee warming her hands, she felt a profound sense of permanence. For years she had designed spaces for others. Looking down at the vibrant street, she finally felt she belonged in one.\n\n5.\nWalking to her SoMa office last year, at 44, she felt a familiar surge of pride passing a mixed-use building she\u2019d guided through approvals. Then she saw him: a man, clearly unhoused, huddled for warmth in the recessed entryway she had fought for, a space designed for \u201cpedestrian comfort and activation.\u201d Pride curdled into a sharp, hollow ache. It wasn't enough to make a city beautiful. Her work had to do more. Her definition of a successful project fractured and remade itself in that moment, from aesthetic triumph to human necessity."
